                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1"
                        >Baker, Charles</persName>/83: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1"
                            type="to">Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-25T17:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 25, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>154. For the Minister. Your April 23, noon, and Department’s 151, April 23, 2
                    p.m. Department desires that you continue your supervision of the efforts being
                    made to obtain release of <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_BCC1">Captain
                        Baker</persName> but suggests advisability of your instructing
                        <persName>Peck</persName> to give the case his special attention by
                    following closely all developments and constantly keeping the matter before the
                    ranking officials at Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CWR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
